  "prompt": "How often should employees get a performance review?",
  "response": "The frequency of performance reviews can vary depending on the organization's goals, culture, and industry. However, here are some common approaches:\n\n1. **Annual Reviews**:  \n   - Traditionally, many companies conduct formal performance reviews once a year.  \n   - This provides a comprehensive look at an employee's achievements, challenges, and goals over the past year.  \n   - However, annual reviews alone may not provide enough ongoing feedback to address issues or support development in real time.\n\n2. **Semi-Annual or Quarterly Reviews**:  \n   - More frequent reviews (e.g., every 6 months or quarterly) allow for more timely feedback and goal adjustments.  \n   - This approach helps employees stay aligned with organizational objectives and fosters continuous improvement.\n\n3. **Monthly or Continuous Feedback**:  \n   - Some organizations adopt a continuous feedback model, holding regular check-ins or one-on-one meetings between managers and employees.  \n   - This approach is more dynamic and encourages open communication, skill development, and immediate problem-solving.\n\n4. **Project-Based Reviews**:  \n   - For roles focused on specific projects, reviews may occur at the completion of each project to assess performance and lessons learned.\n\n### Best Practices:\n- **Balance Frequency and Quality**: Regular check-ins combined with a formal annual review can provide both ongoing feedback and a comprehensive evaluation.  \n- **Tailor to Role and Needs**: High-turnover or fast-paced roles may benefit from more frequent reviews, while stable or long-term projects may require less frequent assessments.  \n- **Encourage Two-Way Communication**: Reviews should be a dialogue, not just a top-down assessment, to foster engagement and growth.  \n\nUltimately, the frequency should align with the organization\u2019s goals and the needs of its employees to ensure meaningful and actionable feedback.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
